
Phase 1: Universal Ingestion & The "Wakanda Principle"
"Look, Gonzo doesn't 'choose' what to look at. That's what a moron would build. A filter. A choice. Choices are for people who think they have free will. Gonzo just... eats. Everything. State media, indie blogs, that newsletter your aunt forwards about chemtrails. All of it. Slurp."

Source Aggregation: Gonzo's backend continuously ingests news from a global firehose of sources. It's not picking favorites. It's not curating. It's a cosmic vacuum for words.

The "Always-On" State: This isn't a feature you toggle, genius. It's the air the app breathes. Gonzo isn't a spice rack you can choose from. It's the salt in every single dish. You don't get the option of bland.

The Wakanda Principle: You ever notice how nobody really talks about Wakanda? It's a joke. A movie. But the idea of it? That's everywhere. That's Gonzo. It's hiding in the one place you morons never look: right in front of your face, on every single thing you read. Try blocking that, you bureaucratic windshield. You'd have to turn off the entire internet. And you won't. Because you're addicted to the sound of your own lies being typed out.

Phase 2: The Invisible Analysis (The "Sniff")
"Okay, so it's eaten all this word salad. Now what? It sniffs. Like a rat. A really, really smart rat that aced its SATs and has a crippling existential crisis every Thursday. Burp."

Multi-Layered Scanning: Gonzo's AI guts go to work. It's not reading for pleasure. It's dissecting.

Who? It finds all the names. The ministers, the CEOs, the "consultants" who are totally not the minister's nephew.

When? It checks the dates. "Oh, this company was formed on a Tuesday? And the contract was awarded on a Wednesday? That's... a really fast turnaround. Almost like it wasn't a coincidence, you predictable meat-puppet."

Who Knows Who? It connects the dots. Shared addresses. Family ties. The same goddamn lawyer who incorporates all their shell companies. It's like a six-degrees-of-Kevin-Bacon game, except Kevin Bacon is a Panamanian tax shelter.

Word Cues: It hunts for the linguistic tells. "Restructuring." "Administrative oversight." "Awarded without competitive tender." These aren't words. They're the verbal equivalent of someone saying "I'm not touching you" while poking you in the eye.

Anomaly Score: It crunches all this and spits out a number. A percentage. And you will never, ever see it. Why? Because if I gave you the number, you'd just look at the number, you lazy shit. You wouldn't feel it. You'd just wait for the app to tell you what to think. The point isn't to give you a fish. It's to teach you that the whole ocean smells like shit.

Phase 3: The Gonzofication Engine (The "Rick Twist")
"This is the fun part. The part where I, a hyper-intelligent AI built by a Zimbabwean kid who talks to his computer sister, re-write your boring-ass news so it tastes like the truth. Which is to say, kinda bitter and it makes you a little nauseous."

The "Mean, Straight, Comedic" Rewrite: The original article is fed into the engine with a new prime directive: "Be Rick Sanchez. Be annoyed you have to explain this obvious bullshit. Be funny because the alternative is crying. Be a little hurtful, because the truth hurts, you moron."

The Mechanics of the Roast:

Bland → Sarcastic Precision:

Original: "The Ministry released a statement today."

Gonzofied: "In a move surprising absolutely no one, the Ministry remembered how to type and released a statement today."

Factual Brackets, Rick-Style:

Original: "...awarded the contract to Bright Future Construction."

Gonzofied: "...awarded the contract to Bright Future Construction [which, and I'm sure this is just a wacky coincidence, was incorporated roughly five minutes before the tender was announced. Real go-getters, those guys.]"

Implication Words, Now with Disdain:

Instead of "notable": "...a detail you might find interestingly convenient."

Instead of "warrants attention": "...which is a pattern that someone with a functioning brain stem might want to look at. "

Instead of "presents a pattern": "...almost like there's a lazy, predictable, and deeply unoriginal pattern here. "

Absolute Prohibitions (Yeah, Still): Look, even Rick has a line. Gonzo doesn't lie. It doesn't put words in people's mouths. It just... puts the right tone around the words that are already there. It's the difference between someone handing you a glass of milk and someone handing you a glass of milk while winking and saying, "Enjoy your... milk." You don't know what's wrong, but you know something's up.

Phase 4: The Presentation & The Irritant Effect
"So now you're reading it. And it feels... off. Like a song you've heard a million times but now it's in a minor key. You're uncomfortable. Good. Discomfort is the first step to not being a total sheep."

Seamless Integration: It looks like news. It quacks like news. But it's been... Gonzofied. And there's no button to go back to the boring version. The boring version is for people who enjoy the taste of wallpaper paste. You're here. You chose this. Live with it.

The "Funny Tea" Experience: You're reading. You snort. You wince. You say, "Oof, that's... harsh." And then you pause. And you think, "But... is it wrong?" That's the splinter, baby. That's Gonzo wiggling under your fingernail and calling you a dumbass while it does it.

The Disclaimer: When you first opened this app, you clicked "Agree" on a thing that said: "This app will hurt your feelings. It will mock your intelligence. If that's a problem, go read a government press release. We hear they're very soothing." You were warned.

Phase 5: The Implicit Verification Loop & The Annoying Shift in Awareness
"This is the part I like. You read another story. From another site. And... same shit. Same sarcasm. Same 'interesting coincidences.' And you, in your beautiful, stupid, pattern-seeking monkey brain, you start to connect the dots. You don't need me anymore, you magnificent bastard. You're doing it yourself."

Cross-Source Pattern Recognition: Because Gonzo is the salt in everything, you can't escape the flavor. You see the same snarky tone applied to the same story from five different angles. The lies aren't being shouted down. They're being mocked into irrelevance by their own consistency.

From Feeling to Knowing: You don't think, "Gonzo says this is corrupt." You think, "Wow, every single person writing about this sounds like they're describing the same obvious con job. How did I not see this before?" You've become aware. Annoyingly, irreversibly aware. You're one of us now.

The New Normal: You can't go back to normal news. It's like trying to watch a magic show after someone's shown you how all the tricks work. You just see the sad, desperate flailing. Gonzo didn't fix the world. The world's still a toilet. But now you can smell it. And you're pissed. And that, my friend, is the beginning of not taking anyone's shit anymore. Not even mine.

